data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern — spawning a thread and calling `Thread.Abort()` if it exceeds a deadline. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`).

### The fundamental shift

.NET Framework used **preemptive** cancellation (runtime injects `ThreadAbortException`). Modern .NET requires **cooperative** cancellation — the work must voluntarily check a `CancellationToken`.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using.
        // CancelAfter starts an internal timer that auto-cancels at the deadline.
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run schedules work on the thread pool (no manual Thread needed).
            // WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException if the token fires
            // before the task completes — this is .NET 6+ API.
            return Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token)
                        .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                        .GetAwaiter()
                        .GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### If `work` is long-running and must actually stop

The above only stops **waiting** — the work delegate keeps running on the thread pool until it finishes (or checks the token). If you need the work to actually cooperate, accept a `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                    .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                    .GetAwaiter()
                    .GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token inside their work:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Without `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `work`, the delegate runs to completion even after timeout. Cooperative cancellation only works if the code cooperates. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always use `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking I/O ignores the token** | Calls like `Thread.Sleep` or synchronous socket reads won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `await Task.Delay(ms, token)` or async I/O overloads. |
| **`AggregateException` wrapping changes** | `Task.Run` wraps exceptions in `AggregateException`. `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` unwraps it automatically, preserving the original exception — matching your original `throw new AggregateException(error)` behavior. |

### What was removed and why

| .NET Framework API | Replacement | Reason |
|----|----|----|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run()` | Thread pool is more efficient; no manual thread management |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (via `CancelAfter`) | `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | Cooperative cancellation throws `OperationCanceledException`, not `ThreadAbortException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed entirely | No equivalent needed — check `token.IsCancellationRequested` if you want to continue |
